      </div>
    </aside>
  </div>

  <!-- Quick answer -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-12" id="quick-answer">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">Quick Answer</h2>
      <div class="p-6 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-r from-indigo-50 via-purple-50 to-pink-50 border-l-4 border-indigo-500">
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">
          <strong>Packets per second (PPS)</strong> is the number of individual network packets a link or device handles each second. The same bandwidth produces very different packet rates depending on packet size: <strong class="text-indigo-600">1 Gbps carries ~81,000 PPS with full-size 1,500-byte frames but ~1.49 million PPS with minimum 64-byte frames</strong>.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-2">PPS = link rate in bits/s ÷ (on-wire packet size in bytes × 8)</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- What is PPS -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-8" id="what-is-pps">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">What Is PPS (Packets Per Second)?</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Everything that crosses a network travels in <strong>packets</strong> — self-contained chunks of data, each carrying its own addressing headers. PPS counts how many of those chunks pass a point per second. If bandwidth (Mbps) is the <em>volume of water</em> flowing through a pipe, PPS is the <em>number of bottles</em> that water is divided into. Filling many small bottles is far more work than filling a few big ones — even when the total water is identical.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        That work is the reason PPS exists as a metric: a router, switch, or firewall must parse headers, look up a destination, check ACL rules, and make a forwarding decision <strong>once per packet, regardless of the packet's size</strong>. Hardware datasheets therefore quote two ceilings — a bandwidth rating (Gbps) and a packet-rate rating (PPS or Mpps) — and in real networks the PPS ceiling is very often the one you hit first.
      </p>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4" role="img" aria-label="Same 1 Gbps bandwidth shown as 81 thousand large packets, 244 thousand medium packets, or 1.49 million small packets per second">
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-white border border-teal-100 text-center">
          <div class="text-3xl mb-1">📦</div>
          <div class="font-extrabold text-teal-600 text-xl">81,274 PPS</div>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-xs mt-1">1 Gbps · 1,500B frames<br />(downloads, streaming)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-indigo-50 to-white border border-indigo-100 text-center">
          <div class="text-3xl mb-1">📨</div>
          <div class="font-extrabold text-indigo-600 text-xl">234,962 PPS</div>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-xs mt-1">1 Gbps · 512B frames<br />(DNS, API traffic)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-50 to-white border border-amber-100 text-center">
          <div class="text-3xl mb-1">✉️</div>
          <div class="font-extrabold text-amber-600 text-xl">1,488,095 PPS</div>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-xs mt-1">1 Gbps · 64B frames<br />(ACKs, VoIP, attacks)</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-gray-400 text-xs mt-4 text-center">The same 1 Gbps of bandwidth — an 18× difference in packets the hardware must process. Line-rate values, wire overhead included.</p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- PPS vs Mbps -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-8" id="pps-vs-mbps">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">PPS vs Mbps: Two Ceilings, One Network</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Bandwidth tests answer "how many bits fit through per second?" — but they usually test with large packets, which is the <em>easiest</em> case for hardware. A device can pass a 1 Gbps speed test flawlessly and still collapse under 200,000 small packets per second, because per-packet processing — not bit-moving — is its true bottleneck. This is why:
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-6">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-indigo-500 font-bold">•</span><span><strong>VoIP and gaming</strong> stress networks more than their tiny bandwidth suggests: a G.711 voice call is only ~0.09 Mbps but generates 50 packets every second, and a busy game server sends thousands of sub-256-byte updates per second.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-indigo-500 font-bold">•</span><span><strong>Firewalls slow down as features turn on:</strong> stateful inspection, NAT, and IPS each add per-packet work, so effective PPS drops with every enabled feature while the bandwidth rating on the box stays the same.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-indigo-500 font-bold">•</span><span><strong>Cloud instances have PPS quotas:</strong> major cloud providers cap packets per second per VM type — a workload can be throttled on packet rate while using a fraction of its bandwidth allowance.</span></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
        If you only remember one thing: <strong>bandwidth is capacity, PPS is workload.</strong> Size your hardware for the packet rate of your worst-case traffic mix, not the bandwidth of your best-case speed test. To translate between bandwidth units first, use our <a href="/converters/mbps-to-mbs/" class="text-indigo-600 hover:underline font-medium">Mbps to MB/s converter</a> or <a href="/" class="text-indigo-600 hover:underline font-medium">Mbps to Bytes converter</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Formula -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-8" id="formula">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">The PPS Formula (Done Right)</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The math is one division — the accuracy is entirely in what you divide by. On Ethernet, every frame is preceded by an 8-byte preamble/start-delimiter and followed by a mandatory 12-byte inter-frame gap. Those <strong>20 extra bytes occupy the wire for every single packet</strong>, so the correct per-packet cost is the frame size <em>plus 20 bytes</em>:
      </p>
      <div class="p-6 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-white border border-teal-100 mb-6 text-center">
        <code class="text-teal-700 text-lg font-bold">PPS = link rate (bits/s) ÷ ((frame bytes + 20) × 8)</code>
      </div>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Worked Example: the Famous 14.88 Mpps</h3>
      <div class="space-y-3 mb-8">
        <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-indigo-100 text-indigo-600 font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">A 10 Gbps link carries minimum-size 64-byte frames → on-wire size = 64 + 20 = <strong>84 bytes = 672 bits</strong></span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-indigo-100 text-indigo-600 font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">10,000,000,000 bits/s ÷ 672 bits = <strong class="text-indigo-600">14,880,952 PPS ≈ 14.88 Mpps</strong></span>
        </div>
        <div class="flex gap-3 items-start">
          <span class="w-7 h-7 rounded-lg bg-indigo-100 text-indigo-600 font-bold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</span>
          <span class="text-gray-600">14.88 Mpps is the exact figure used in <a href="https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2544" rel="noopener" target="_blank" class="text-indigo-600 hover:underline">RFC 2544</a> line-rate benchmarks for 10 GbE — if the formula didn't include overhead, this industry-standard number wouldn't exist.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-4">Reverse Direction: PPS → Required Bandwidth</h3>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
        Multiply instead of divide: <code class="text-gray-700 font-semibold">bit rate = PPS × (frame bytes + 20) × 8</code>. Example: a monitoring dashboard shows 500,000 PPS of ~512-byte traffic → 500,000 × 532 × 8 = <strong>2.13 Gbps</strong> of wire bandwidth. The calculator above works in both directions — enter either side.
      </p>
    </div>
